  <rdf:Description rdf:about="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_instances/so_MLE#Method/Interpolation_12037/32_25_61">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_schema/so_MLE#Method"/>
    <so:method_name>Interpolation</so:method_name>
    <so:textual_span>Optimal Interpolation (OI) technique</so:textual_span>
    <so:has_sentence_context rdf:resource="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_instances/so_MLE#Sentence/12037/32"/>
    <so:description>In the mathematical field of numerical analysis, interpolation is a type of estimation, a method of constructing (finding) new data points based on the range of a discrete set of known data points. In engineering and science, one often has a number of data points, obtained by sampling or experimentation, which represent the values of a function for a limited number of values of the independent variable.</so:description>
    <so:wikipedia_url>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=14569</so:wikipedia_url>
  </rdf:Description>
  <rdf:Description rdf:about="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_instances/so_MLE#Method/Microscopy_12302/17_31_47">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_schema/so_MLE#Method"/>
    <so:method_name>Microscopy</so:method_name>
    <so:textual_span>light microscopy</so:textual_span>
    <so:has_sentence_context rdf:resource="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_instances/so_MLE#Sentence/12302/17"/>
    <so:description>Microscopy is the technical field of using microscopes to view subjects too small to be seen with the naked eye (objects that are not within the resolution range of the normal eye). There are three well-known branches of microscopy: optical, electron, and scanning probe microscopy, along with the emerging field of X-ray microscopy.</so:description>
    <so:wikipedia_url>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=19567</so:wikipedia_url>
  </rdf:Description>
