  <rdf:Description rdf:about="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_instances/so_MLE#Article/23674">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_schema/so_MLE#Article"/>
    <so:title>New records of rare species in the Mediterranean Sea (October 2020)</so:title>
    <so:article_ID>https://ejournals.epublishing.ekt.gr/index.php/hcmr_med_mar_sc/article/view/23674</so:article_ID>
    <so:publication_year rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#integer">2020</so:publication_year>
    <so:publisher>Mediterranean Marine Science</so:publisher>
    <so:doctype>['Scientific article', 'Publication in journal']</so:doctype>
  </rdf:Description>
  <rdf:Description rdf:about="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_instances/so_MLE#Method/Linear_regression_12070/59_88_114">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_schema/so_MLE#Method"/>
    <so:method_name>Linear regression</so:method_name>
    <so:textual_span>multiple linear regression</so:textual_span>
    <so:has_sentence_context rdf:resource="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_instances/so_MLE#Sentence/12070/59"/>
    <so:description>In statistics, linear regression is a model that estimates the relationship between a scalar response (dependent variable) and one or more explanatory variables (regressor or independent variable). "Linear regression is linear in its unknown parameters ( i.e., the parameters appear only to the first power) not necessarily in variables." From a mathematical perspective, X and Y are treated as variables, and the parameters are considered fixed constants but from a statistics perspective, the focus is on the parameters.</so:description>
    <so:wikipedia_url>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=48758386</so:wikipedia_url>
  </rdf:Description>
