  <rdf:Description rdf:about="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_instances/so_MLE#Method/Pearson_correlation_coefficient_12224/37_0_20">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_schema/so_MLE#Method"/>
    <so:method_name>Pearson correlation coefficient</so:method_name>
    <so:textual_span>Pearson correlations</so:textual_span>
    <so:has_sentence_context rdf:resource="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_instances/so_MLE#Sentence/12224/37"/>
    <so:description>In statistics, the Pearson correlation coefficient (PCC), also known as Pearson's r, the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient (PPMCC), or simply the unqualified correlation coefficient, is a correlation coefficient that measures linear correlation between two sets of data. It is the ratio between the covariance of two variables and the product of their standard deviations; thus, it is essentially a normalized measurement of the covariance, such that the result always has a value between −1 and 1.</so:description>
    <so:wikipedia_url>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=221708</so:wikipedia_url>
  </rdf:Description>
